docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When Rod J. Rosenstein, the deputy attorney general, headed to the White House on Monday morning, he was ready to resign and convinced — wrongly, it turned out — that President Trump was about to fire him. docs.abstract: A confirmation effort that was once seen as an island of functionality in a chaotic White House has become the latest messy episode in a presidency full of them.
docs.snippet: A confirmation effort that was once seen as an island of functionality in a chaotic White House has become the latest messy episode in a presidency full of them.
docs.lead_paragraph: BERKELEY HEIGHTS, N.J. — As the fate of Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh, his Supreme Court nominee, teetered over a sexual assault allegation from decades ago, President Trump vented his frustration about his own party’s unwillingness to aggressively hit back.

headline.main: Constrained From Fighting, Trump Is Left a Spectator With Kavanaugh in Peril

headline.main: Trump Stands by ‘Fantastic’ Kavanaugh as He Seeks G.O.P. Votes

docs.abstract: Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh has calendars from the summer of 1982 that do not show a party consistent with the allegation against him. But his team acknowledges they do not disprove the accusation.

Kavanaugh has calendars from the summer of 1982 that he plans to hand over to the Senate Judiciary Committee that do not show a party consistent with the description of his accuser, Christine Blasey Ford, according to someone working for his confirmation.

headline.main: Kavanaugh to Give Senate Calendars From 1982 to Back Up Denial

docs.abstract: The Federal Reserve raised interest rates for the third time this year and signaled it was on track to raise them again in December.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Federal Reserve’s chairman, Jerome H. Powell, said on Wednesday that the American economy was experiencing “a particularly bright moment” as the Fed announced a widely expected increase in its benchmark interest rate and signaled that it planned to continue raising rates.

docs.abstract: The rise of nonwage compensation like paid time off is helping persuade the Fed to push up interest rates.
docs.snippet: The rise of nonwage compensation like paid time off is helping persuade the Fed to push up interest rates.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — One of the most perplexing questions about the nation’s economic recovery is why a tight labor market has not translated into faster wage growth. Part of the answer appears to be that American workers are receiving a growing share of compensation in the form of benefits rather than wages.

headline.main: One Reason for Slow Wage Growth? More Benefits
headline.print_headline: In Lieu of Higher Wages, Companies Turn to Perks
